1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,833
Problem: biodiversity evidence is fragmented. Occurrence

2
00:00:03,833 --> 00:00:07,667
records may live in one system, DNA barcode fragments in

3
00:00:07,667 --> 00:00:11,500
another, BLAST or Sequence ID tables in a lab pipeline, and

4
00:00:11,500 --> 00:00:15,333
publication metadata in spreadsheets. When these pieces are

5
00:00:15,333 --> 00:00:19,167
not connected, useful evidence can be lost, and species-level

6
00:00:19,167 --> 00:00:23,000
claims can become stronger than the data actually support.

7
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:26,667
EcoGenesis is a Barcode-to-GBIF Evidence Compiler. It takes

8
00:00:26,667 --> 00:00:30,333
DNA barcode, metabarcoding, Sequence ID and BLAST-like

9
00:00:30,333 --> 00:00:34,000
outputs, then runs deterministic evidence gates. The result is

10
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:37,667
not just a label. It is a safe taxonomic rank decision, a

11
00:00:37,667 --> 00:00:41,333
publication-readiness state, a repair plan, and a reproducible

12
00:00:41,333 --> 00:00:45,000
Evidence Pack.

13
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,500
On the public demo site, the interface is organized around the

14
00:00:48,500 --> 00:00:52,000
whole evidence path. Judges can open the overview, run the

15
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:55,500
compiler, inspect the evidence map, view the fragment graph,

16
00:00:55,500 --> 00:00:59,000
check validation, read methods and download the Evidence Pack.

17
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,500
Each section has its own public route, so the workflow is easy

18
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:06,000
to review and cite.

19
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:10,200
The Run Compiler screen is where molecular evidence enters the

20
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:14,400
system. A user can upload a CSV, start from a demo workflow,

21
00:01:14,400 --> 00:01:18,600
or test a reference fragment. The compiler validates required

22
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:22,800
molecular fields, sequence context, reference-hit metrics, and

23
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:27,000
publication metadata before it lets any record move forward.

24
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:30,500
In the mixed demo, records do not collapse into one simplistic

25
00:01:30,500 --> 00:01:34,000
answer. Some are species-safe, some are genus-safe, some

26
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,500
remain weak, and some are not publishable until metadata are

27
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:41,000
repaired. This is the core behavior: useful molecular evidence

28
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,500
is preserved, but unsafe species exports and incomplete

29
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:48,000
publication records are stopped.

30
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:51,500
The Evidence Map turns the results into a spatial evidence

31
00:01:51,500 --> 00:01:55,000
atlas. It connects GBIF occurrence context with claim states,

32
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:58,500
snapshot hashes, VSEA rows, graph objects and export

33
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:02,000
boundaries. The map is not a proof of presence by itself; it

34
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,500
is a way to inspect provenance, context and claim strength in

35
00:02:05,500 --> 00:02:09,000
one place.

36
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,600
In the live Evidence Map, reviewers can see which rows are

37
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:16,200
safe, repair-required, review-only or blocked. The same view

38
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:19,800
exposes judge-mode checks, graph audits and export boundaries

39
00:02:19,800 --> 00:02:23,400
before download. That makes the spatial layer explanatory and

40
00:02:23,400 --> 00:02:27,000
auditable rather than a visual shortcut.

41
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:30,600
The Fragment Graph shows how marker fragments link to

42
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:34,200
reference taxa and safe LCA decisions. When a fragment points

43
00:02:34,200 --> 00:02:37,800
to multiple close taxa, EcoGenesis reports the most specific

44
00:02:37,800 --> 00:02:41,400
safe rank instead of forcing a species claim. This keeps

45
00:02:41,400 --> 00:02:45,000
evidence, competitors and caveats together.

46
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:48,800
Uncertainty is handled through explicit gates: identity and

47
00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:52,600
coverage, ambiguity and LCA downgrade, barcode gap, diagnostic

48
00:02:52,600 --> 00:02:56,400
k-mer support, marker profile, publication readiness and graph

49
00:02:56,400 --> 00:03:00,200
provenance. A top hit does not become a species-level output

50
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:04,000
unless the required gates pass.

51
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,833
Validation is built into the submission package. The project

52
00:03:07,833 --> 00:03:11,667
includes backend tests, frontend tests, competition batches,

53
00:03:11,667 --> 00:03:15,500
adversarial batches, graph audits and contest-readiness

54
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:19,333
checks. The important validation target is fail-closed

55
00:03:19,333 --> 00:03:23,167
behavior: weak coverage, close competitors, metadata gaps and

56
00:03:23,167 --> 00:03:27,000
unsafe exports must be blocked or downgraded.

57
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:31,200
The final deliverable is the Evidence Pack. It includes CSV,

58
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:35,400
JSON, HTML, VSEA, graph and audit outputs for review, repair

59
00:03:35,400 --> 00:03:39,600
and reuse. Researchers can inspect sequence safety tables,

60
00:03:39,600 --> 00:03:43,800
publication blockers, molecular evidence reports, graph

61
00:03:43,800 --> 00:03:48,000
provenance and machine-readable export artifacts.

62
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,375
EcoGenesis is already a working contest prototype with a live

63
00:03:51,375 --> 00:03:54,750
demo, public source code, reproducible outputs and

64
00:03:54,750 --> 00:03:58,125
downloadable evidence artifacts. It can scale to larger

65
00:03:58,125 --> 00:04:01,500
reference libraries, institutional pipelines, richer GBIF

66
00:04:01,500 --> 00:04:04,875
publishing workflows and broader molecular evidence

67
00:04:04,875 --> 00:04:08,250
observatories. The call to action is simple: open the live

68
00:04:08,250 --> 00:04:11,625
demo, run the workflow, and inspect the evidence before

69
00:04:11,625 --> 00:04:15,000
publication.
